      <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">When you can claim compensation</h2>
      <p class="govuk-body">Compensation is money paid to make up for loss, damage or injury caused by a crime. It’s a court-ordered payment.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">You may be able to claim compensation or apply for benefit payments if you’ve been affected by a crime.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">This includes if you:</p>
      <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
        <li>are a victim of a crime</li>
        <li>are a close relative of someone who has died because of a crime</li>
        <li>witnessed a serious crime, were involved or seriously injured</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Criminal compensation orders</h2>
      <p class="govuk-body">If someone is convicted of a crime, the court can order them to pay you compensation. Depending on the circumstances of the case, this could be for:  </p>
      <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
        <li>personal injury</li>
        <li>losses from theft or damage to property</li>
        <li>losses from fraud</li>
        <li>being off work</li>
        <li>medical expenses</li>
        <li>travel expenses</li>
        <li>pain and suffering</li>
        <li>loss, damage, or injury caused by a stolen vehicle</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="govuk-body">There’s no limit on the amount of compensation that can be given under a criminal order. The amount will depend on what the court considers appropriate after looking at the case.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">They will consider what’s fair, and any evidence and issues raised by:</p>
      <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
        <li>the person convicted of the crime – for example, how much they can afford to pay without getting into unmanageable debt</li>
        <li>the prosecutor – for example, how much compensation you’re hoping for</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Criminal injuries compensation scheme</h2>
      <p class="govuk-body">You might be able to claim compensation if you were the victim of a violent crime. This includes if:</p>
      <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
        <li>you were physically or mentally injured</li>
        <li>you were the victim of sexual assault</li>
        <li>a close relative died</li>
        <li>you saw the crime happen to a loved one (or were there immediately afterwards)</li>
        <li>you paid for the funeral of a person who died</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="govuk-body">You usually have to claim within 2 years of the crime. The crime must be reported to the police before you apply.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/claim-compensation-criminal-injury" class="govuk-link" target="_blank">Claim compensation if you were the victim of a violent crime (opens in a new tab)</a>.</p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Civil compensation</h2>
      <p class="govuk-body">You can make a claim through a civil court. A civil court deals with non-criminal, private cases between people or companies.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">For example, you could claim compensation for personal injury, assault or damage to property.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">You should get legal advice first, as the process can be difficult and expensive.</p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Claiming benefits</h2>
      <p class="govuk-body">Depending on your circumstances, there might be benefits you can claim.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">You may be entitled to <a href="https://www.gov.uk/browse/benefits/bereavement" class="govuk-link" target="_blank">benefits and financial support when someone dies (opens in new tab)</a>.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">If you're refused a benefit and you disagree, you can <a href="https://www.gov.uk/appeal-benefit-decision" class="govuk-link" target="_blank">appeal a benefits decision (opens in new tab)</a>.</p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Insurance for your property</h2>
      <p class="govuk-body">You can check your home or car insurance policy to see if it covers the crime you experienced, for example theft or vandalism to your property.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">If someone committed a crime to your property and you have their details, you might be able to make a claim against their insurance policy.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">If an insurance company refuses a claim and you disagree, you can complain to the <a href="https://www.financial-ombudsman.org.uk/consumers/how-to-complain" class="govuk-link" target="_blank">Financial Ombudsman Service (opens in new tab)</a>.</p>

      <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">Employment insurance</h2>
      <p class="govuk-body">If the crime involved an injury or death that happened at your work, you might be able to make an insurance claim against your employer.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">Most employers are legally required to have insurance to cover employees for injury, illness, or death that occurs as a result of their work.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">You would need to document the incident and instruct a solicitor who sends a "letter of claim" to your employer or their insurer.</p>
      <p class="govuk-body">You can get more advice on employment issues from <a href="http://www.acas.org.uk/" class="govuk-link" target="_blank">Acas (opens in new tab)</a>.</p>

    </div>
